Bidirectional Forwarding Detection (BFD)
for the Pseudowire Virtual Circuit
Connectivity Verification (VCCV)
2010", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC5885.html", target="_top", tooltip="This document describes Connectivity Verification (CV) Types using Bidirectional Forwarding Detection (BFD) with Virtual Circuit Connectivity Verification (VCCV).  VCCV provides a control channel that is associated with a pseudowire (PW), as well as the corresponding operations and management functions such as connectivity verification to be used over that control channel. [STANDARDS-TRACK]"];
  cites -> RFC5885;
  RFC6426 [label="RFC6426
MPLS On-Demand Connectivity Verification
and Route Tracing
2011", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC6426.html", target="_top", tooltip="Label Switched Path Ping (LSP ping) is an existing and widely deployed Operations, Administration, and Maintenance (OAM) mechanism for Multi-Protocol Label Switching (MPLS) Label Switched Paths (LSPs).  This document describes extensions to LSP ping so that LSP ping can be used for on-demand connectivity verification of MPLS Transport Profile (MPLS-TP) LSPs and pseudowires.  This document also clarifies procedures to be used for processing the related OAM packets.  Further, it describes procedures for using LSP ping to perform connectivity verification and route tracing functions in MPLS-TP networks.  Finally, this document updates RFC 4379 by adding a new address type and creating an IANA registry. [STANDARDS-TRACK]"];
  cites -> RFC6426;
  RFC6435 [label="RFC6435
MPLS Transport Profile Lock Instruct and
Loopback Functions
2011", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC6435.html", target="_top", tooltip="Two useful Operations, Administration, and Maintenance (OAM) functions in a transport network are lock and loopback. The lock function enables an operator to lock a transport path such that it does not carry client traffic, but can continue to carry OAM messages and may carry test traffic. The loopback function allows an operator to set a specific node on the transport path into loopback mode such that it returns all received data. This document specifies the lock function for MPLS networks and describes how the loopback function operates in MPLS networks. This document updates Sections 7.1.1 and 7.1.2 of RFC 6371. [STANDARDS-TRACK]"];
  cites -> RFC6435;
  RFC6478 [label="RFC6478
Pseudowire Status for Static Pseudowires
2012", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC6478.html", target="_top", tooltip="This document specifies a mechanism to signal Pseudowire (PW) status messages using a PW associated channel (ACh).  Such a mechanism is suitable for use where no PW dynamic control plane exits, known as static PWs, or where a Terminating Provider Edge (T-PE) needs to send a PW status message directly to a far-end T-PE.  The mechanism allows PW Operations, Administration, and Maintenance (OAM) message mapping and PW redundancy to operate on static PWs.  This document also updates RFC 5885 in the case when Bi-directional Forwarding Detection (BFD) is used to convey PW status-signaling information. [STANDARDS-TRACK]"];
  cites -> RFC6478;
